From: edwin@maui.cs.ucla.edu (Edwin Tisdale)
Subject: Gateway 2000 Pentium Linux
Date: 30 Oct 93 03:13:31 GMT

The memory bus in Gateway 2000 "Best Buy" computers is clocked
at the same speed as the 60 MHz Pentium processor and moves 64 bits
at a time between the processor and the 70 nanosecond Dynamic RAM.
They use Intel's 32-bit 30 MHz PCI bus instead of the VESA Local Bus
architecture used by AMBRA.  They have a larger hard disk drive
but only a 16-bit 30 MHz disk controller.  You will wait at least
SEVEN WEEKS for delivery from the day you place your order.

I was able to get the information I needed from Gateway 2000 immediately.
Their Sales Representatives new much more about their product than their
counterparts at AMBRA knew about theirs.

Gateway 2000 will NOT install Linux or any other software options.

I called the toll free number (1-800-846-2063) for Gateway 2000
and got Sales Representative Monroe Beauchene at extension 5684.
He quoted me a price of $2995 for their "Best Buy" Pentium based
system which includes:

*       60 MHz Intel Pentium processor with 256KB 20 ns cache
*       8MB 70 ns system memory expandable to 128MB
*       4 ISA, 2 PCI and 1 ISA/PCI combination slots
*       Tower case with 30O-watt power supply
*       424MB Western Digital IDE hard disk drive
*       16-bit, 30 MHz disk controller
*       14", 0.28mm dot pitch non-interlaced Super VGA color monitor
*       1280x1024 PCI ATI ULTRA XLR with 2MB DRAM
*       1 parallel and 2 serial ports
*       Keyboard and Microsoft mouse

This system does not have nearly all the features of a Sun SPARCstation 10
Model 30.  But it should be sufficient to compare the performance of the two
systems.  All we need is for someone to put their money where my mouth is.

Monroe Beauchene did mention that Gateway 2000 has a University program
under which it might be possible to obtain one of these systems for 30 days
evaluation if we could find someone to install Linux and run benchmarks.
Bob Tisdale (edwin@cs.ucla.edu)

